<subsection xml:id="subsec-simplifying-algebraic-fractions">
    <title>Simplifying algebraic fractions</title>
    <p>
        Algebraic fractions are fractions that have algebraic expressions in their numerators,in denominators or with them.
    </p>
    <p>
        <term>Factorization method of simplification</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        Have you ever shared something equally among friends, like sharing food? When working with algebraic fractions, we apply similar ideas by finding common terms and simplifying them.
    </p>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>Group Activity: </term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>What you need:</term> A book or a paper and a pen
            </p>
            <p>
                A mechanic workshop has two workers, Amani and Baraka. Amani completes <m>\frac {1}{3}</m> of a car repair job in an hour, while Baraka completes <m>\frac {1}{4}</m> of the same job in an hour.
            </p>
            <p>
                Taking any given letter to represent the total amount of work, find:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            How much work do they complete together in one hour?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            How do we express this as a simplified algebraic fraction?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Guide:</term> 
            </p>
            <p>
                We can simplify algebraic fractions the same way we simplify numerical fractions
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the Least Common Multiple (LCM)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Rewrite fractions with the same denominator
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Combine like terms, then simplify
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Simplify the algebraic fraction:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \frac {x}{3} + \frac {2x}{4}
                </me>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Find the LCM of <m>3</m> and <m>4</m> <m>-&gt;</m>  <m>12</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Rewrite each fraction
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \frac {x}{3} + \frac {2x}{4} = \frac {4(x) + 3(2x)}{12}
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    = \frac {4x + 6x}{12}
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Add the numerators
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \frac {10x}{12}
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Now, simplify;
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \frac {5x}{6}
                </me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
        Sometimes we simplify fractions with <m>like terms</m> and sometimes <m>unlike terms.</m>
    </p>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Simplify the algebraic expression, <m>\frac {3}{4} a + \frac {5}{6} b</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Find the LCM of the denominators
            </p>
            <p>
                The denominators are <m>4</m> and <m>6</m>, getting <m>12</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Rewrite each fraction with denominator <m>12</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \frac {3}{4} a + \frac {5}{6} b = \frac {9a + 10b}{12} 
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Since the terms are unlike (one has <m>'a'</m> and the other has <m>'b'</m>), we cannot combine them, therefore;
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \frac {9a + 10b}{12} 
                </me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Simplify the algebraic fraction:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \frac {3x + 9}{6x + 18}
                </me>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First we need to factor out the common factors in the numerator and denominator
            </p>
            <p>
                The numerator <m> 3x + 9 </m> has a common factor of <m> 3 </m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    3x + 9  = 3( x + 3) 
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                The denomenator <m> 6x + 18 </m> has a common factor of <m> 6 </m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    6x + 18 = 6 ( x + 3)
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Rewriting the fraction with factored forms:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \frac {3 ( x + 3)}{6 ( x + 3)}
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                The common factor <m>( x + 3)</m> cancels out having:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \frac {3 ( x + 3)}{6 ( x + 3)} = \frac {3}{6}
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \frac {3}{6} = \frac {1}{2}
                </me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A farmer employed three workers and paid them <m>\frac {4}{5} p</m>, <m>\frac {2}{3} p</m> and <m>\frac {3}{4} p</m> shillings respectively. Calculate the total amount paid and simplify your answer.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Simplify each of the following expressions:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ol marker = "a)">
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac {3}{7} y</m> + <m>\frac {5}{7} y</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac {a + 4}{6} </m> + <m>\frac {a}{4} </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac {x - 3}{5} </m> + <m>\frac {x + 2}{4} </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac {5}{6} p</m> + <m>\frac {2}{9} p</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac {2m + 6}{m + 3} </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac {5y - 10}{15y + 30} </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Shillah is given <m>\frac {2}{5} g</m> litres of water in a container and <m>\frac {3}{8} g</m> litres in another. He pours all the water into a large tank. Find the total amount of water in the tank and simplify your answer.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The length of a football field is <m>\frac {5}{6} t</m> metres by <m>\frac {2}{3} t</m> metres. Find its perimeter and simplify your answer.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For a tilling job Jeff, Ham and Steve were paid <m>\frac {7}{8} n</m> shillings, <m>\frac {2}{3} n</m> shillings and <m>\frac {5}{12} n</m> shillings respectively. Calculate the total amount of money they were paid for the tilling work and simplify the answer.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Munene's piece of land has an area of <m>\frac {9x - 12}{3x}</m> hectares. What is the simplified form of this expression?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Sakina's farm produce <m>\frac {6m - 9}{3m + 3}</m> of maize in a particular year. Express the amount of maize in its simplest form.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Ministry of education receives <m>\frac {5k + 10}</m> shillings from the budgetary board. It spends <m>\frac {5k + 10}{10}</m> on digital learning for the classrooms resources. What fraction of its budget is it allocated for digital learning? Simplify your answer.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>

</subsection>